particular phenomenon of wearing the headscarf itself, with the authors confronting broader issues of lasting import. These issues include the questions of safeguarding individual and collective identity in a diverse democracy, exploring the ways in which identities inform and shape political practices, and sourcing the meaning of citizenship and belonging in the United States through the voices of Muslim-American women themselves.The Politics of the Headscarf in the United States superbly melds quantitative data with qualitative assessment, and the authors smoothly integrate the results of nearly two thousand survey responses from Muslim-American women across forty-nine states. Seventy-two in-depth interviews with Muslim women living in the United States bolster the arguments put forward by the authors to provide an incredibly well-rounded approach to this fascinating topic.Ultimately, the authors argue, women’s experiences with identity and boundary construction through their head-covering practices carry important political consequences that may well shed light on the future of the United States as a model of democratic pluralism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aClothing and dressxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aHijab (Islamic clothing)xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aHijab (Islamic clothing)xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aIslamzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aMuslim womenxClothingzUnited States. 0aMuslim womenzUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 4aCivil Rights Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh  ahijab, Islamophobia, Muslim-American Identity.1 aRussell, Özge Çelik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWestfall, Aubrey L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/